{
  "texts": [
    "For example, the Adam optimizer stores the \"first moment\" and \"second moment\" of trainable parameters.Pan et al. [4] provides a comprehensive empirical comparison between full fine-tuning and LoRA fine-tuning on an LLaMA2-7B model with batch size 1, utilizing a single NVIDIA RTX4090 (24 GB) GPU.",
    "According to this study, full fine-tuning requires approximately 60 GB of memory, which exceeds the capacity of an RTX4090 GPU; by contrast, LoRA fine-tuning only needs about 23 GB of memory.",
    "LoRA significantly reduces memory usage and makes fine-tuning LLaMA2-7B feasible on a single NVIDIA RTX4090 (24 GB) GPU.",
    "Specifically, due to fewer trainable parameters, both optimization memory and gradient memory decrease significantly by approximately 25 GB and 14 GB respectively.",
    "On the other hand, while LoRA introduces additional 1.9×\"incremental parameters\" resulting in slight increases in activation memory and weight memory (totaling about 2 GB), this increase is negligible when considering the overall reduction in memory."
  ]
}